specs.implementationPlan:
All changes in /home/ogutd/msword-clone/src/renderer/js/commands.js (plus a small CSS hook). Mirror the existing Layout-menu pattern.

1. One-time setup of lang on the editor for CSS hyphens to work: in app/editor init (or lazily inside the handler the first time), ensure E().node has lang="en" — `#editor` currently has no lang attribute (only <html lang="en"> exists). CSS `hyphens:auto` requires a lang on or above the element; relying on <html lang> works in Chromium/Electron, but set `E().node.lang = 'en'` defensively. Also add `-webkit-hyphens` for Chromium (Electron): set both `hyphens` and `webkitHyphens`.

2. Register handler near the other Layout handlers (commands.js ~line 156-161):
   H.hyphenation = (c, node) => hyphenationMenu(node);
   And add a routing case in the dropdown() switch (commands.js ~352-375, alongside margins/orientation/size/columns):
   if (cmd === 'hyphenation') return hyphenationMenu(node);

3. Add module-level state + apply function (near setPageVar / layout menus ~line 667):
   const hyphState = { mode: 'none', caps: true, zone: 0.25, limit: 0 };
   function applyHyphenation(mode) {
     hyphState.mode = mode;
     const ed = E().node;
     ed.lang = ed.lang || 'en';
     // 'manual' is approximated as 'manual' CSS (only &shy; break) -> but we run a pass; treat live mode as auto-off
     if (mode === 'automatic') { ed.style.hyphens = 'auto'; ed.style.webkitHyphens = 'auto'; }
     else if (mode === 'manual') { ed.style.hyphens = 'manual'; ed.style.webkitHyphens = 'manual'; }
     else { ed.style.hyphens = 'none'; ed.style.webkitHyphens = 'none'; }
     E().repaginate(); E().dirty = true;
   }

4. hyphenationMenu(node):
   WC.flyout(node, (fly) => {
     const item = (label, mode) => { const it = WC.flyItem(label, { onClick: () => { applyHyphenation(mode); } }); if (hyphState.mode === mode) it.classList.add('toggled'); return it; };
     fly.appendChild(item('None', 'none'));
     fly.appendChild(item('Automatic', 'automatic'));
     fly.appendChild(WC.flyItem('Manual', { onClick: () => runManualHyphenation() }));
     fly.appendChild(WC.flySep());
     fly.appendChild(WC.flyItem('Hyphenation Options...', { onClick: () => hyphenationOptionsDialog() }));
   });
   (Check the actual flyItem checkmark convention — other menus use .classList.add('toggled') / markChecked(); match whatever marks an active item.)

5. hyphenationOptionsDialog(): build body with WC.el rows (checkboxes + number inputs seeded from hyphState), then:
   WC.dialog({ title:'Hyphenation', width:'360px', body, footer:[
     { label:'Manual...', onClick: () => { commitFields(); runManualHyphenation(); } },
     { label:'OK', primary:true, onClick: () => { commitFields(); applyHyphenation(autoCheckbox.checked ? 'automatic' : 'none'); } },
     { label:'Cancel' } ] });
   commitFields() reads caps/zone/limit into hyphState. Note in code that zone/limit are stored and influence the manual pass + a toast, but CSS hyphens:auto cannot honor a numeric zone (browser limitation) — store for fidelity and surface via toast like other partial features do.

6. runManualHyphenation(): the real, buildable approximation. Walk visible text words in E().node (use a TreeWalker over text nodes inside block elements). For each word longer than ~6 chars that isn't all-CAPS-when-caps-disabled, compute candidate break points with a lightweight syllable splitter (regex on vowel/consonant boundaries, e.g. split before a consonant+vowel that follows a vowel; cap to avoid 1-2 char fragments and respect "limit consecutive hyphens"). Show the "Manual Hyphenation" dialog per candidate word via WC.dialog showing the word with a highlighted proposed break and Yes/No/Cancel buttons; on Yes, insert a soft hyphen (­, &shy;) at the chosen split in that text node so it only renders at line end. Drive it as a queue (one dialog at a time; Yes/No advances, Cancel stops). When done, WC.toast('Hyphenation complete.'). Because a full Word-grade per-word interactive walk over a large doc is heavy, scope the pass to a reasonable cap (e.g. first N candidate words) and note the approximation in a toast — consistent with how trackChanges/spellCheck flag approximations in this codebase.

7. CSS: add to editor.css a rule so soft hyphens and auto hyphenation render: `#editor { hyphens: none; -webkit-hyphens: none; }` as the inert default (so toggling inline style controls it). Soft hyphens (­) render automatically regardless. Optionally honor `hyphenate-limit-chars` if supported, but treat as best-effort.

Note: Word's default is None, so do not enable anything at startup; the handler only changes state on user action.

specs.uiNeeded:
Yes — a new ribbon control renderer for type "spinner" plus CSS.

Layout: In Word these sit as two stacked rows in the Paragraph group: row 1 = "Indent" with two label+spinner pairs (Left, Right); row 2 = "Spacing" with two label+spinner pairs (Before, After). Reuse the existing .ctrl-stack / .ctrl-row flex layout already used for small controls.

Each spinner widget (call it .rspin) = a tiny left label (e.g. icon or text "Left:") + a number <input> (~46px wide, right-aligned) + a stacked up/down arrow column (two small buttons, ~12px each). Model it on the existing .rcombo markup (input + .combo-arrow) but with two stacked arrows instead of one dropdown caret.

New CSS in /home/ogutd/msword-clone/src/renderer/styles/ribbon.css (after the .rcombo block ~line 189-206):
  .rspin { display:inline-flex; align-items:center; height:22px; border:1px solid var(--btn-border,#bcbcbc); border-radius:2px; background:#fff; }
  .rspin .spin-lbl { font-size:11px; color:#444; padding:0 4px; white-space:nowrap; }  (or put the label OUTSIDE the box, to the left, matching Word which shows the field label to the left)
  .rspin input { width:40px; border:0; outline:0; font-size:11px; text-align:right; padding:0 2px; }
  .rspin .spin-btns { display:flex; flex-direction:column; width:14px; border-left:1px solid var(--btn-border,#ddd); }
  .rspin .spin-btns button { flex:1; border:0; background:transparent; font-size:7px; line-height:1; cursor:pointer; padding:0; }
  .rspin .spin-btns button:hover { background:var(--btn-hover); }
  .spin-field { display:flex; align-items:center; gap:4px; }  (wraps a text label + .rspin)

Per Word, render a leading text label ("Left", "Right" under an "Indent" caption; "Before", "After" under "Spacing"). Simplest faithful approach: each control = <span class="spin-field"><span class="spin-cap">Left:</span><div class="rspin">…</div></span>; pack the two Indent fields in one .ctrl-row and the two Spacing fields in another, inside a .ctrl-stack.
